# JavaFX UI

## Structure

- Controllers/Views only handle UI state and user actions; they call application services, never domain or drivers directly.
- Bind UI to ViewModels or observable properties (e.g. `Property<Double>`, `ObservableList`) so the chart and labels update when the service pushes new data.

## Threading

- All UI updates must run on JavaFX Application Thread. When receiving data from a driver or Flow, use `Platform.runLater { ... }` or `runOnFxThread` equivalent before updating controls.
- Do not block the FX thread: move I/O and device communication to coroutines or background threads.

## Charts

- Use one main chart for temperature vs time (and optionally RoR). Prefer a library that supports live updates (e.g. JFreeChart-FX or JavaFX Canvas). Avoid rebuilding the whole chart on every sample; append points or update last segment.
- Keep chart configuration (axis labels, units °C/°F) in a single place or injected from app settings.

## Naming and files

- FXML (if used) next to or under the same package as the controller. One controller per screen or major widget. Use ControlSFX where it fits (e.g. extra controls); fallback to standard JavaFX controls.
